GO
/************************************************************************************************

Program:  		owf_CalcWorkingDaysBetweenDates
Author:			Alan Groves
Date created:	22/11/2016		
											
Description:   

This function takes two date parameters and counts the number of working days (i.e. 
Monday-Friday) between the two dates inclusive of the two dates.

Although the function accepts datetime values, the time portion is effectively ignored 
and the start and end dates are included. Only whole days are returned which explains
why the time portion is ignored. Also, bank holidays are not taken into account.

Additionally, if the number of days evaluates 

As an example, start date 22/11/2016 03:34:09 and end date 30/11/2016 11:56:23 will 
return the value 7 i.e. 7 working days between the two dates including the two dates.

This function is called as follows:

	declare @StartDate datetime, @EndDate datetime
	set @StartDate	= '2016-11-22 03:34:09'
	set @EndDate	= '2016-11-30 11:56:23'
	select dbo.owf_CalcWorkingDaysBetweenDates(@StartDate,@EndDate)

This function was initially developed to populate the following column:	

	dbo.mi_insight_CaseCheckOutcomes.CaseCheckDays
									
Amendment History								
-----------------								
											
Date		Who			Description				
----		---			-----------			
23/11/2016	A Groves	SR456151/CH15222. Customer Outcomes project.
						When the Start Date and End Date are the same and fall on the weekend, 
						then the number of days returned is zero. Sandra Hale asked for this 
						function to always return a minimum of 1 day.
************************************************************************************************/

CREATE FUNCTION [dbo].[owf_CalcWorkingDaysBetweenDates] (@StartDate datetime, @EndDate datetime)
returns int
as 

begin

	declare @Days integer

	set @Days = ((datediff(day,0,@EndDate)-datepart(dw,@EndDate))-(datediff(day,0,@StartDate)-datepart(dw,@StartDate)))/7*5				--[weekdays]
				+ datepart(dw,@EndDate) - datepart(dw,@StartDate)																		--[weekday diff]
				+ case when datediff(day,0,@StartDate) > datediff(day,0,@EndDate) then -1 else 1 end									--[start after]
				+ case when datediff(day,0,@StartDate) > datediff(day,0,@EndDate) and datepart(dw,@StartDate) = 7 then 1 else 0 end		--[start after and start saturday]
				+ case when datediff(day,0,@StartDate) > datediff(day,0,@EndDate) and datepart(dw,@EndDate) = 1 then 1 else 0 end		--[start after and end sunday]
				+ case when datediff(day,0,@StartDate) <= datediff(day,0,@EndDate) and datepart(dw,@StartDate) = 1 then -1 else 0 end	--[start not after and start sunday]
				+ case when datediff(day,0,@StartDate) <= datediff(day,0,@EndDate) and datepart(dw,@EndDate) = 7 then -1 else 0 end		--[start not after and end saturday]

	if @Days < 1
		set @Days = 1
		
	return @Days 

end



